03817nam a22005055i 9780226667393DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266673937 a10.7208/97802266673932doi  a(DE-B1597)523139  a(OCoLC)793511379  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ127.G3 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a500.20943/09034a500.20943090341 aPhillips, Denise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAcolytes of Nature :bDefining Natural Science in Germany, 1770-1850 /cDenise Phillips. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Natural Knowledge and the Learned Public in the Enlightenment -- t2. The Expanding Ranks of Nature’s Friends -- t3. Defending Learned Dignity -- t4. Nature in a Local Microcosm -- t5. Wooing the Polite Public -- t6. The Nature of the Fatherland -- t7. The Wellspring of Modernity -- t8. The Particularity of Natural Science -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough many of the practical and intellectual traditions that make up modern science date back centuries, the category of “science” itself is a relative novelty. In the early eighteenth century, the modern German word that would later mean “science,” naturwissenschaft, was not even included in dictionaries. By 1850, however, the term was in use everywhere. Acolytes of Nature follows the emergence of this important new category within German-speaking Europe, tracing its rise from an insignificant eighteenth-century neologism to a defining rallying cry of modern German culture. Today’s notion of a unified natural science has been deemed an invention of the mid-nineteenth century. Yet what Denise Phillips reveals here is that the idea of naturwissenschaft acquired a prominent place in German public life several decades earlier. Phillips uncovers the evolving outlines of the category of natural science and examines why Germans of varied social station and intellectual commitments came to find this label useful. An expanding education system, an increasingly vibrant consumer culture and urban social life, the early stages of industrialization, and the emergence of a liberal political movement all fundamentally altered the world in which educated Germans lived, and also reshaped the way they classified knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSciencezGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226667393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226667393.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles